# 🚀 The Professional Developer's Guide
### Master Daily Reporting, Code Maintenance, & Code Reviews

Welcome! Adopting professional software engineering habits early is one of the fastest ways to grow from a hobbyist coder to a senior-level engineer. This guide details industry-standard practices for **Status Reporting**, **File/Code Maintenance**, and **Code Reviews**.

---

## 📋 1. Making Professional Status Reports

In the industry, developers report their daily work in **Daily Standups** (15-minute quick syncs) or **Written Weekly/Daily Status Reports**. 

### 💡 The Golden Rule of Reporting
A professional status report should answer three simple questions for your team and managers:
1. **What did I accomplish since the last update?** (Keep it action-oriented and positive).
2. **What will I focus on next?** (Shows forward momentum).
3. **Are there any blockers?** (Enables team members to help you).

### 📝 The Professional Daily Log Template
When writing daily logs (like the ones we created in the `report/` folder), use a structure like this:

```markdown
# Daily Log - [Date]

## 🎯 Focus / Goal
A one-sentence summary of the main objective for the day.

## 🛠️ Achievements / Done
* **[Component/Feature Name]**: What was done + why (e.g. "Configured JWT verification middleware to secure admin-only API routes").
* **[Bug Fixes]**: What was resolved (e.g. "Resolved Redux state mutation bug where profile updates crashed the UI on refresh").

## 📂 Key Files Touched
* `src/components/Navigation.jsx` (Modified)
* `controllers/user.controller.js` (Added)

## 🚧 Blockers / Impediments
* (e.g. "Waiting on API token details for Stripe integration" or "None").

## ⏩ Next Steps
* What is the immediate task for tomorrow?
```

### 🧠 Senior Tip: Let Git Tell the Story
Don't rely on memory! At the end of the day, use Git commands to retrieve exact details:
* `git status` — Lists what files you are currently modifying.
* `git log --oneline --author="Your Name"` — Shows your commits for the day.
* `git diff --stat HEAD~1` — Shows exactly which files changed and how many lines were added/deleted since the last commit.

